spec: ab3391
version: ">=3.9"
backend: python_module(abc)

docs: https://docs.python.org/3/library/abc.html

provenance:
  derived_from:
    - "https://docs.python.org/3/library/abc.html"
    - "Test vectors verified with Python 3.14.4 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-13"
  not_derived_from:
    - "CPython source code"
    - "any proprietary source"
  notes:
    - "Wave 673 (ab3391): __int__, __float__, __complex__ dict-presence (int(x), float(x), complex(x)) for abc module types."
    - "Theme: __int__/__float__/__complex__ dict-presence (int(x), float(x), complex(x))."
    - "All values False — abc types are abstract base class machinery with no numeric conversion support."
    - "All values verified with Python 3.14.4 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-13."
    - "Classes covered: abc.ABC, abc.ABCMeta, and type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) — the built-in function type."
    - "Key finding (__int__): all 3 abc subjects return false for __int__. int() delegates to __int__ (numbers.Integral protocol) when defined. abc types implement no numeric protocol. abc.ABC is a plain abstract base class convenience wrapper with no integer semantics — int(ABC) is not a defined Python expression. abc.ABCMeta is a metaclass responsible for abstract method tracking and virtual subclass registration (__subclasshook__, register(), __abstractmethods__); integer conversion has no role in ABCMeta's responsibilities. The function type (type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) is <class 'function'>) does not define __int__ — functions are callables and descriptors, not integers. int(f) is not a valid Python expression for function objects."
    - "Key finding (__float__): all 3 abc subjects return false for __float__. float() delegates to __float__ (numbers.Real protocol). abc types define no numeric protocol of any kind — confirmed false across waves 658–672 for all arithmetic, bitwise, reflected, in-place augmented assignment, unary numeric, and rounding operators. float(ABC) is not a valid Python expression for an abstract base class helper. float(ABCMeta) is not defined — ABCMeta's entire capability is in class-hierarchy machinery, not numeric computations. float(f) is not defined for the function type — function objects are callable descriptors with no real-valued magnitude."
    - "Key finding (__complex__): all 3 abc subjects return false for __complex__. complex() delegates to __complex__ (numbers.Complex protocol). abc types are not complex number types. abc.ABC is a pure abstract base class helper; it cannot be converted to a complex number. abc.ABCMeta is a metaclass; ABCMeta.__complex__() and complex(ABCMeta) are not defined Python operations. The function type does not define __complex__ — functions are callable descriptors, not complex numbers. complex(f) where f is a plain function raises TypeError because __complex__ is absent."
    - "All 9 values in this wave are false — continuing the all-false pattern from wave 672 (__trunc__/__round__/__index__)."
    - "The function type profile across all waves: true only for __get__ (wave 652), __repr__ (wave 655), and __call__ (wave 656). All other dunders tested — including this wave's __int__/__float__/__complex__ — are false."
    - "abc.ABCMeta has now returned false for every arithmetic, bitwise, reflected, in-place augmented assignment, unary numeric, numeric rounding, numeric truncation, integer-index, and numeric conversion dunder tested across 22 consecutive waves (652–673). Its entire capability is expressed through class-hierarchy machinery, not operator overloading."
    - "Cross-wave summary for abc subjects:"
    - "  Wave 652 (ab3076): __get__ true for function type; __set__/__delete__ false."
    - "  Wave 653 (ab3091): __hash__/__eq__/__bool__ all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 654 (ab3106): __lt__/__le__/__gt__ all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 655 (ab3121): __ge__ false; __repr__ true for function type only; __str__ false."
    - "  Wave 656 (ab3136): __call__ true for function type only; __len__/__getitem__ false."
    - "  Wave 657 (ab3151): __setitem__/__delitem__/__contains__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 658 (ab3166): __add__/__sub__/__mul__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 659 (ab3181): __truediv__/__floordiv__/__mod__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 660 (ab3196): __pow__/__lshift__/__rshift__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 661 (ab3211): __and__/__or__/__xor__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 662 (ab3226): __radd__/__rsub__/__rmul__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 663 (ab3241): __rtruediv__/__rfloordiv__/__rmod__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 664 (ab3256): __rpow__/__rlshift__/__rrshift__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 665 (ab3271): __rand__/__ror__/__rxor__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 666 (ab3286): __iadd__/__isub__/__imul__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 667 (ab3301): __itruediv__/__ifloordiv__/__imod__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 668 (ab3316): __ipow__/__ilshift__/__irshift__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 669 (ab3331): __iand__/__ior__/__ixor__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 670 (ab3346): __neg__/__pos__/__abs__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 671 (ab3361): __invert__/__floor__/__ceil__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 672 (ab3376): __trunc__/__round__/__index__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 673 (ab3391): __int__/__float__/__complex__ — all false for all 3."
  created_at: "2026-04-13"

error_model: python_exceptions

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# __int__ dict-presence — operator.contains(Cls.__dict__, '__int__')
#
# All 3 abc subjects return false for __int__.
# int() delegates to __int__ (numbers.Integral protocol) when defined.
# abc.ABC: a plain abstract base class convenience wrapper with no integer
#   semantics. int(ABC) is not a defined Python expression.
# abc.ABCMeta: a metaclass for abstract method tracking and virtual subclass
#   registration. Integer conversion has no role in ABCMeta's responsibilities
#   (__subclasshook__, register(), __abstractmethods__). int(ABCMeta)
#   is not a valid Python expression.
# type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) is <class 'function'>:
#   functions do not define __int__. int(f) is not a valid Python expression
#   for callable objects. Functions are callables and descriptors with no
#   integer data model.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

table ab3391.int:
  description: "abc types __int__ dict-presence checks; wave 673"
  kind: python_call_eq
  version: ">=3.9"
  error_model: python_exceptions
  category: dict_contains
  id_prefix: ab3391

  columns: [id, function, args, expected]
  rows:
    - ["ab3391001", operator.contains, [abc.ABC.__dict__,                                 "__int__"], false]
    - ["ab3391002", operator.contains, [abc.ABCMeta.__dict__,                             "__int__"], false]
    - ["ab3391003", operator.contains, [type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)).__dict__,  "__int__"], false]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# __float__ dict-presence — operator.contains(Cls.__dict__, '__float__')
#
# All 3 abc subjects return false for __float__.
# float() delegates to __float__ (numbers.Real protocol). abc types define
#   no numeric protocol of any kind — confirmed false across waves 658–672 for
#   all arithmetic, bitwise, reflected, in-place augmented assignment, unary
#   numeric, and numeric rounding operators.
# abc.ABC: no numeric data model; float(ABC) is not a defined Python expression.
#   abc.ABC is a pure abstract base class helper with no state of its own
#   beyond what ABCMeta provides.
# abc.ABCMeta: does not define __float__. ABCMeta's API surface
#   (__subclasshook__, register(), __abstractmethods__) has no arithmetic,
#   bitwise, or float conversion component. float(ABCMeta) is not valid.
# type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) is <class 'function'>:
#   functions do not define __float__. float(f) is not a valid Python expression
#   for callable objects. The function type is tightly scoped to its role as
#   a callable descriptor with a display representation.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

table ab3391.float:
  description: "abc types __float__ dict-presence checks; wave 673"
  kind: python_call_eq
  version: ">=3.9"
  error_model: python_exceptions
  category: dict_contains
  id_prefix: ab3391

  columns: [id, function, args, expected]
  rows:
    - ["ab3391004", operator.contains, [abc.ABC.__dict__,                                 "__float__"], false]
    - ["ab3391005", operator.contains, [abc.ABCMeta.__dict__,                             "__float__"], false]
    - ["ab3391006", operator.contains, [type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)).__dict__,  "__float__"], false]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# __complex__ dict-presence — operator.contains(Cls.__dict__, '__complex__')
#
# All 3 abc subjects return false for __complex__.
# complex() delegates to __complex__ (numbers.Complex protocol). abc types are
#   not complex number types.
# abc.ABC: a pure abstract base class helper; ABC cannot be converted to a
#   complex number. complex(ABC) raises TypeError because __complex__ is absent.
# abc.ABCMeta: a powerful metaclass, but its entire power lies in class-
#   hierarchy machinery — not in complex number representation. ABCMeta.__complex__()
#   and complex(ABCMeta) are not valid Python operations.
# type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) is <class 'function'>:
#   functions do not define __complex__. Unlike int and float (which can
#   be converted to complex), CPython's built-in function type has no
#   __complex__. complex(f) raises TypeError; f cannot be used as a complex
#   number.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

table ab3391.complex:
  description: "abc types __complex__ dict-presence checks; wave 673"
  kind: python_call_eq
  version: ">=3.9"
  error_model: python_exceptions
  category: dict_contains
  id_prefix: ab3391

  columns: [id, function, args, expected]
  rows:
    - ["ab3391007", operator.contains, [abc.ABC.__dict__,                                 "__complex__"], false]
    - ["ab3391008", operator.contains, [abc.ABCMeta.__dict__,                             "__complex__"], false]
    - ["ab3391009", operator.contains, [type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)).__dict__,  "__complex__"], false]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# combined — __int__, __float__, __complex__ across all 3 abc subjects
#
# Covers the full matrix: 3 classes x 3 methods = 9 rows.
# __int__: false for all 3.
# __float__: false for all 3.
# __complex__: false for all 3.
# All 9 values are false.
# Continues the all-false pattern from wave 672 (__trunc__/__round__/__index__).
# The function type profile across all waves tested:
#   true:  __get__ (652), __repr__ (655), __call__ (656)
#   false: __set__, __delete__, __hash__, __eq__, __bool__, __lt__, __le__, __gt__,
#          __ge__, __str__, __len__, __getitem__, __setitem__, __delitem__,
#          __contains__, __add__, __sub__, __mul__, __truediv__, __floordiv__,
#          __mod__, __pow__, __lshift__, __rshift__, __and__, __or__, __xor__,
#          __radd__, __rsub__, __rmul__, __rtruediv__, __rfloordiv__, __rmod__,
#          __rpow__, __rlshift__, __rrshift__, __rand__, __ror__, __rxor__,
#          __iadd__, __isub__, __imul__, __itruediv__, __ifloordiv__, __imod__,
#          __ipow__, __ilshift__, __irshift__, __iand__, __ior__, __ixor__,
#          __neg__, __pos__, __abs__, __invert__, __floor__, __ceil__,
#          __trunc__, __round__, __index__, __int__, __float__, __complex__
# The function type is tightly scoped to its role as a callable descriptor
#   with a display representation. All arithmetic, bitwise, reflected,
#   in-place augmented assignment, unary numeric, numeric rounding, numeric
#   truncation, integer-index, and numeric conversion operators are absent.
# abc.ABCMeta note: ABCMeta has now returned false for every arithmetic,
#   bitwise, reflected, in-place augmented assignment, unary numeric, numeric
#   rounding, and numeric conversion dunder tested across 22 consecutive waves
#   (652–673). Its power lies exclusively in class-hierarchy machinery — not
#   in operator overloading of any kind.
# abc.ABC note: ABC is a pure syntactic convenience for declaring abstract base
#   classes. It has no state of its own beyond what ABCMeta provides, and defines
#   no arithmetic, bitwise, reflected arithmetic, power/shift, reflected bitwise
#   logical, in-place augmented assignment, unary numeric, numeric rounding,
#   numeric truncation, integer-index, or numeric conversion protocol whatsoever.
# Cross-wave summary for abc subjects:
#   Wave 652 (ab3076): __get__ true for function type; __set__/__delete__ false.
#   Wave 653 (ab3091): __hash__/__eq__/__bool__ all false for all 3.
#   Wave 654 (ab3106): __lt__/__le__/__gt__ all false for all 3.
#   Wave 655 (ab3121): __ge__ false; __repr__ true for function type only; __str__ false.
#   Wave 656 (ab3136): __call__ true for function type only; __len__/__getitem__ false.
#   Wave 657 (ab3151): __setitem__/__delitem__/__contains__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 658 (ab3166): __add__/__sub__/__mul__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 659 (ab3181): __truediv__/__floordiv__/__mod__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 660 (ab3196): __pow__/__lshift__/__rshift__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 661 (ab3211): __and__/__or__/__xor__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 662 (ab3226): __radd__/__rsub__/__rmul__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 663 (ab3241): __rtruediv__/__rfloordiv__/__rmod__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 664 (ab3256): __rpow__/__rlshift__/__rrshift__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 665 (ab3271): __rand__/__ror__/__rxor__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 666 (ab3286): __iadd__/__isub__/__imul__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 667 (ab3301): __itruediv__/__ifloordiv__/__imod__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 668 (ab3316): __ipow__/__ilshift__/__irshift__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 669 (ab3331): __iand__/__ior__/__ixor__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 670 (ab3346): __neg__/__pos__/__abs__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 671 (ab3361): __invert__/__floor__/__ceil__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 672 (ab3376): __trunc__/__round__/__index__ — all false for all 3.
